    What does the U.S. Supreme Court do?
    About the U.S. Supreme Court:

    Their terms do not expire meaning they hold their position for life. The U.S. Supreme court hears cases that challenge the constitution, interprets legislation, protects civil rights, deals with disputes between states, and presides over cases that involve treaties.

    Can the Supreme Court ruling be overturned?
    When the Supreme Court rules on a constitutional issue, that judgment is virtually final; its decisions can be altered only by the rarely used procedure of constitutional amendment or by a new ruling of the Court.

    Description

    The Supreme Court of the United States is the highest court in the federal judiciary of the United States. It has ultimate appellate jurisdiction over all U.S. federal court cases, and over state court cases that turn on questions of U.S. constitutional or federal law. Wikipedia
    Founded: March 4, 1789
    Established: September 24, 1789
    Official name: The Supreme Court of the United States
